{
    "level": "B1",
    "intro": "In this topic you will learn how to use <strong>collective nouns</strong> such as <strong>team, family, staff, police</strong> and how to match them with the verb.",
    "rules": [
        {
            "label": "ONE GROUP",
            "color": "emerald",
            "text": "When the group is seen as <strong>one unit</strong>, a singular verb is often natural.",
            "example": "The team is ready."
        },
        {
            "label": "MEMBERS",
            "color": "blue",
            "text": "When the focus is on the <strong>members inside the group</strong>, especially in BrE, a plural verb is possible.",
            "example": "The team are wearing different shirts."
        },
        {
            "label": "SPECIAL CASES",
            "color": "amber",
            "text": "Some words have their own pattern: <strong>police</strong> is almost always plural.",
            "example": "The police are investigating the case."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "1. Common collective nouns",
    "intro": "Remember the usual words and their behaviour.",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "often singular",
            "title": "team / family / class / committee",
            "subtitle": "The family is happy."
        },
        {
            "label": "singular or plural",
            "title": "staff / audience / government",
            "subtitle": "depends on meaning and variety of English"
        },
        {
            "label": "usually plural",
            "title": "police",
            "subtitle": "The police are here."
        },
        {
            "label": "meaning decides",
            "title": "couple / crew / company",
            "subtitle": "one unit or separate members?"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "2. How to choose the form",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "The group as one unit",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "When you talk about the group as <strong>a single whole</strong>, singular form sounds natural.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "The team is ready for the match.",
                    "ua": "The team is ready for the match."
                },
                {
                    "en": "My family lives in Lviv.",
                    "ua": "My family lives in Lviv."
                },
                {
                    "en": "The committee has made its decision.",
                    "ua": "The committee has made its decision."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "The members separately",
            "color": "blue",
            "description": "In British English, a plural verb is possible when the focus is on <strong>the people inside the group</strong>.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "The team are wearing different shirts.",
                    "ua": "The team are wearing different shirts."
                },
                {
                    "en": "My family are all coming at different times.",
                    "ua": "My family are all coming at different times."
                },
                {
                    "en": "The staff are arguing about the schedule.",
                    "ua": "The staff are arguing about the schedule."
                }
            ],
            "note": "American English more often keeps the singular in these cases."
        },
        {
            "label": "Special cases",
            "color": "amber",
            "description": "<strong>Police</strong> almost always takes a plural verb; other nouns depend on the meaning.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "The police are outside.",
                    "ua": "The police are outside."
                },
                {
                    "en": "The audience was silent.",
                    "ua": "The audience was silent."
                },
                {
                    "en": "The audience were taking their seats.",
                    "ua": "The audience were taking their seats."
                }
            ],
            "note": "The same noun can take different agreement depending on what you want to highlight."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "3. Common mistakes",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Mistake 1",
            "color": "rose",
            "title": "Using police with a singular verb.",
            "wrong": "The police is here.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">The police are here.</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 2",
            "color": "amber",
            "title": "Using plural automatically for every collective noun.",
            "wrong": "My family are small. <span class=\"text-slate-500\">(if you mean the family as one unit)</span>",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">My family is small.</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 3",
            "color": "sky",
            "title": "Ignoring the meaning focus.",
            "wrong": "The team is wearing different shirts. <span class=\"text-slate-500\">(if the focus is on individual players)</span>",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">The team are wearing different shirts.</span>"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "4. Quick summary",
    "items": [
        "Collective nouns name a group of people or things as one unit.",
        "Singular is natural when the group is seen as a whole.",
        "Plural is possible when the individual members matter, especially in BrE.",
        "<strong>Police</strong> usually takes a plural verb.",
        "The right choice depends not only on the noun, but also on the meaning in the sentence."
    ]
}

